The paper deals with distributed network algorithms and complexity theory, which are typically studied in the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The focus on locality and communication rounds also suggests the sub-category of Computational Complexity (cs.CC). The use of neighborhood inspection and certificate verification suggests the sub-categories of Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) and Information Theory (cs.IT), respectively. Finally, the study of randomized algorithms and completeness results suggests the sub-category of Machine Learning (cs.LG).
